05372nam a22008175i 9780231550406DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018058411  a97802315504067 a10.7312/sidm193582doi  a(DE-B1597)526859  a(OCoLC)1104711729  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJK1976b.S58 2019 7aPOL0300002bisacsh04a324.9732231 aSidman, Andrew H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPork Barrel Politics :bHow Government Spending Determines Elections in a Polarized Era /cAndrew H. Sidman. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b31 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Incumbents and Pork Barrel Politics -- t2. Pursuing the Pork Barrel -- t3. An Electoral History of the Pork Barrel -- t4. Attitudes, Voting, and the Pork Barrel -- t5. Challenges from Within the Party -- t6. General-Election Challengers and Campaigns -- t7. Election Outcomes -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConventional wisdom holds that legislators who bring “pork”—federal funds for local projects—back home to their districts go a long way toward fending off potential challengers. For more than four decades, however, the empirical support for this belief has been mixed. Some studies have found that securing federal spending has no electoral effects at best or can even cost incumbent legislators votes.In Pork Barrel Politics, Andrew H. Sidman offers a systematic explanation for how political polarization affects the electoral influence of district-level federal spending. He argues that the average voter sees the pork barrel as an aspect of the larger issue of government spending, determined by partisanship and ideology. It is only when the political world becomes more divided over everything else that the average voter pays attention to pork, linking it to their general preferences over government spending. Using data on pork barrel spending from 1986 through 2012 and public works spending since 1876 along with analyses of district-level outcomes and incumbent success, Sidman demonstrates the rising power of polarization in United States elections. During periods of low polarization, pork barrel spending has little impact, but when polarization is high, it affects primary competition, campaign spending, and vote share in general elections. Pork Barrel Politics is an empirically rich account of the surprising repercussions of bringing pork home, with important consequences in our polarized era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGovernment spending policyzUnited States. 0aGovernment spending policy-United States. 0aPolarization (Social sciences)xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolarization (Social sciences)-Political aspects-United States. 0aUnited States.-Congress-Appropriations and expenditures. 0aUnited States.-Congress-Elections. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / National.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/sidm1935840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978023155040642